modules.description: Converts IPv6 prefixes to and from S-expression format, and provides comparison functionality for prefix objects. Operates on IPv6 address prefixes and associated address types. Used for serialization and ordered comparison in network configuration parsing.

Converts IPv4 prefixes to and from S-expression format, and provides comparison functionality for prefix equality and ordering. Operates on IPv4 address prefixes, extracting and comparing their network address and prefix length. Used to serialize and deserialize network configurations in a structured, readable format.

Serializes and deserializes IPv4 address prefixes using S-expressions, enabling structured representation of network configurations. Supports comparison operations to check equality and order prefixes based on their network address and prefix length. Users can convert between human-readable S-expression formats and internal representations for network processing. Examples include parsing configuration files, validating prefix ranges, and sorting prefixes for routing tables.

Encodes and decodes IPv6 prefixes using S-expressions, enabling structured data representation and parsing. Supports comparison operations to order and evaluate prefix relationships. Handles IPv6 address types and prefix notations, facilitating network configuration management. Examples include serializing a prefix for storage and comparing two prefixes to determine precedence.

Converts IP address prefixes to and from S-expression format, and provides comparison functionality. Operates on IP address prefix data structures derived from the Ipaddr module. Useful for serialization and ordered processing of network prefixes in configuration or protocol handling.

Handles conversion and validation of IP addresses between string and binary formats for both IPv4 and IPv6. Manages MAC address parsing, formatting, and comparison. Validates input formats and ensures correct representation in network byte order.

Provides serialization and deserialization of IPv4 and IPv6 prefixes to and from S-expressions, along with comparison operations for ordering and evaluating prefix relationships. The main data types are prefix representations derived from Ipaddr, with functions to convert between S-expressions and internal structures. Users can parse configuration data, validate prefix ranges, and sort prefixes for routing or network management tasks. Examples include converting a prefix for storage, comparing prefixes for precedence, and ensuring consistent representation in network protocols.
